After presenting the philosophical background of critical theory, the course will examine two key texts: The Dialectic of Enlightenment by Max Horkheimer and Theodor Adorno (1944) and One-Dimensional Man by Herbert Marcuse (1964). Next the issue of culture and cultural criticism will be discussed in selected essays of Walter Benjamin, Siegfried Kracauer and Theodor Adorno. The course concludes with the work of Jürgen Habermas, Judith Butler, and Rahel Jäeggi.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The objective of the course is to familiarize students with contemporary texts of political philosophyLearning outcomes/õpiväljund:  The learning outcomes are a firm understanding of contemporary texts of political and social philosophy. Having passed the course, the student has also improved his or her ability to analyze philosophical texts, his or her presentations skills.

Students will also develop the following skills:

Self-Management Skills - time management, goal setting and self-motivation.

Academic skills - reading academic texts, academic writing and critical thinking.

People skills - how to communicate and participate in team work.

These will be developed during the seminar with group work and include skills for debating and for writing a well structured paper in philosophy.
